   <div id="container2" class="cf"> 
    <article class="span2"> 
     <div class="left">
      <p>The importance of snow water storage in the mountains for summer-time irrigation and food production in downstream states is widely recognized. The process-based modeling of hydrologic systems, including snow processes, is an essential and cost effective tool for our resource management and risk analyses. Our goal is to establish a methodology to estimate snow accumulation, blowing snow, and snowmelt for enhanced water resource management at the watershed and regional scales. </p> 
      <p><strong>Dr. Ohara</strong>, the leader of this group, has been working on snow and watershed hydrology modeling for more than ten years through national and international research projects. A numerical algorithm for snowmelt and snow accumulation processes for very fine scale modeling (~10m grid resolution) was developed and applied to various watersheds around the world. The model solves the depth-averaged snow equations for snow depth, snow surface temperature, and snow density, with consideration of vegetation interception and terrain angles. His snow model is a part of an award-winning, Watershed Environmental Hydrology (WEHY) model system. </p> Dr. Ohara also performed a field experiment at the Ward Creek watershed, Tahoe Basin, California, for snow thermal and runoff processes within a snow-covered hillslope. We are currently conducting a similar field work in the Snowy Range, Wyoming, to quantify the overland/in-snow flow component on the hillslope in very cold climate conditions. 
     </div> 
    </article> 
