    <div class="full-w">
      He has been operating mesoscale numerical weather models such as MM5 &amp; WRF models, for downscaling synoptic scale atmospheric data. These models can reconstruct the regional scale atmospheric data based on NCEP reanalysis data, North American Regional Reanalysis (NARR) data, Global Forecast System (GFS) outputs and General Circulation Model (GCM) outputs. Recently, Ohara has contributed to the research activities for a new estimation methodology of the Probable Maximum Precipitation (PMP) using the MM5 model. He uses high performance computing (HPC) resources at the University of Wyoming, including the NCAR-Wyoming Center (Yellowstone), the UW on-campus cluster (Mt. Moran), and the department cluster (Snowy). 
     <p>Dr. Ohara is actively involved in the Wyoming Center for Environmental Hydrology and Geophysics (WyCEHG) EPSCoR Research Infrastructure Improvement (RII) Track-1 project, funded by NSF. He operates a weather station, hillslope runoff site, and several shallow aquifer monitoring sites in the Snowy Range, Wyoming.</p> 
